Total outbreak: 5 / 0 / 0 / 5 // 229 / 50 / 0 / 279 // 309

*Data in WHO as of 15 Nov 2011 for 2011 data and 13 Nov 2012 for 2012 data.

Afghanistan
-----------
- No new WPV cases were reported in the past week. The total number of WPV cases for 2012 remains 27. The most recent case had onset of paralysis on [1 Oct 2012] (WPV1 from Paktya province).
- The campaign in November [2012] will be held in border areas with Pakistan, and will use a combination of trivalent OPV and bivalent OPV (depending on the area, in response either to recent WPV1 cases in the area, or in response to detection of a circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 outbreak -- cVDPV2 -- across the border in Pakistan).

Nigeria
-------
- No new WPV cases were reported in the past week. The total number of WPV cases for 2012 remains 101. The most recent WPV case had onset of paralysis on [15 Oct 2012] (WPV1 from Katsina).

Pakistan
--------
- 6 new WPV cases were reported in the past week (one WPV1 from Federally Administered Tribal Areas -- FATA -- and 5 WPV1s from Khyber Pakhtunkhwa -- KP), bringing the total number of cases for 2012 to 54. The most recent case was one of the newly reported WPV1 cases from KP with onset of paralysis on [27 Oct 2012].
In addition to transmission of WPV, the country is also responding to a cVDPV2 outbreak (5 cases, all from the greater Quetta area of Balochistan). The most recent NIDs [national immunization days] held in October [2012] had been conducted with trivalent OPV.

Angola
------
- No new cases were reported in the past week. No cases have been reported in 2012. The country reported a total of 5 cases in 2011, and the last case had onset of paralysis on [7 Jul 2011] in Uige in the country's north.
- Planned subnational immunization days were postponed because of government transition.

Chad
----
- No new WPV cases were reported in the past week. The most recently reported WPV case occurred in the Lac region (WPV1) with onset of paralysis on [14 Jun 2012]. The total number of WPV cases for 2012 remains 5.
- Staggered NIDs with trivalent OPV are ongoing in Chad, officially launched by the Prime Minister. The 1st wave (in the south and east) was held on [27-29 Oct 2012], to be followed by the 2nd wave in the north and west on [9-11 Nov 2012]. Staggering the activities allows the deployment of all available technical support to key high-risk areas. Trivalent OPV is used, including to boost immunity levels to type 2 level, in response to the recent confirmation of the cVDPV2 outbreak affecting the country (5 cases in N'Djamena and 2 close to the border with Sudan). Activities are also planned in the Darfur provinces, Sudan, to minimize the risk and consequences of potential spread across the border.

Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)
--------------------------------------
- No new WPV cases were reported in the past week. No WPV cases have been reported in 2012. The total number of WPV cases for 2011 is 93 (all WPV1). The most recent case had onset of paralysis on [20 Dec 2011] in Maniema province.
- Although the country has not reported a WPV case since December 2011, it has been affected by a cVDPV2 outbreak in Katanga province in 2012, with 17 cases reported (most recent case: 4 Apr 2012). Efforts are focused on ensuring the cVDPV2 outbreak is fully stopped.
- In some regions, immunization activities have been postponed because of an ongoing Ebola outbreak.

Horn of Africa
--------------
- Efforts are continuing to stop an ongoing cVDPV2 outbreak in Kenya and parts of Somalia (in a Somali refugee camp in Dadaab, Kenya, and Kismayo, south-central Somalia).
- Immunizations of older age groups have taken place in Dadaab. In Somalia, campaigns have been conducted in border areas with Kenya and Ethiopia, and in some areas of central Somalia (access allowing).

West Africa
-----------
No new WPV cases were reported in the past week. No WPV cases have been reported in 2012. The total number of WPV cases for 2011 in West Africa remains 51 (36 from Cote d'Ivoire, 3 from Guinea, 7 from Mali, and 5 from Niger). The most recent case from the region (WPV1 from Niger) had onset of paralysis on [22 Dec 2011].

