[4] SAGE meeting: OPV2 phaseout
Date: Wed 14 Nov 2012
Source: Global Polio Eradication Initiative [excerpted, edited]
http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek.aspx


- The Strategic Advisory Group of Experts on immunization (SAGE) met last week [week of 5 Nov 2012] in Geneva, Switzerland. During this meeting, the draft polio eradication and endgame strategy for 2013-2018 and current status of the global polio eradication programme were presented to SAGE.
- SAGE endorsed the 4 major objectives and milestones in the new strategic plan. SAGE also recommended that all countries should introduce at least one dose of inactivated polio vaccine (IPV) in their routine immunization programmes to mitigate the risks and consequences associated with the eventual withdrawal of the type 2 component of OPV (OPV2). SAGE will review progress on achieving the pre-requisites for OPV2 withdrawal, including the availability of affordable IPV products, every 6 months to ensure the earliest possible date for OPV2 withdrawal but with sufficient advance notification to ensure programmatic readiness and vaccine availability.

[For more information on the SAGE meeting, follow the links provided at http://www.who.int/immunization/sage/meetings/2012/november/news_sage_ipv_opv_nov2012/en/index.html. Links to all the background documents presented to the SAGE at the 6-8 Nov 2012 meeting can be found at http://www.who.int/immunization/sage/meetings/2012/november/presentations_background_docs/en/index.html. Mod.MPP]

[The reports above paint a picture that is filled with good news and bad news. The exceptionally good news deals with the record low number of reported cases of poliomyelitis in the world -- with the current case count (as of 14 Nov 2012) of a total of 187 cases compared with 520 cases reported during the same time period in 2011. The other good news is that only 4 countries have reported polio cases during 2012 -- Pakistan, Afghanistan, Nigeria, and Chad -- of which Chad is the only non-polio endemic country reporting cases, the date of onset of the last case was 14 Jun 2012, suggesting that the outbreak in Chad may have been contained, and that the other non-endemic countries remain polio free in 2012.

The bad news in the reports above involves the continued obstacles and barriers to vaccination activities and vaccine acceptance in the endemic countries. The safety issues confronting the vaccination teams in the endemic countries and the continued rumors surrounding the safety of the vaccine or rumors speculating nepharious intentions on the part of "the West" to administer sterilizing agents to children.

The other disturbing information in the reports above is the continued appearance of cases of polio associated with infection with circulating vaccine derived poliovirus type 2(cVDPV2) in 6 countries during 2012 -- Pakistan, Chad, Nigeria, Somalia, Kenya, DR Congo (see http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek/Circulatingvaccinederivedpoliovirus.aspx for a table showing the number of cases of polio due to infection with cVDPV by virus type, year and country.) As cases of polio due to infection with cVDPV occur in areas with low vaccination coverages where the vaccine virus is/was able to continue circulation for prolonged periods allowing reversion of the vaccine virus to a more neurovirulent virus, the occurrence of these cases highlights areas that are at risk of WPV circulation if the virus is introduced due to a high number of susceptibles in the population. The recommendation of the Strategic Advisory Group of Experts on immunization (SAGE) that "all countries should introduce at least one dose of inactivated polio vaccine (IPV) in their routine immunization programmes to mitigate the risks and consequences associated with the eventual withdrawal of the type 2 component of OPV (OPV2)" is a recognition that the risk of disease associated with OPV2 is greater than the risk of disease from WPV2 (the last case of polio associated with WPV2 infection in the world was in 1999).

For a map showing the geographic locations of WPV associated cases, see http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring.aspx. For a map showing the geographic locations of cVDPV cases, see http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek/Circulatingvaccinederivedpoliovirus.aspx. - Mod.MPP]
